title: DEBATE: "Does God Exist?" - Michael Jones vs. Dr. Richard Carrier
description:
üôè DONATE: https://inspiringphilosophy.com/give

This is a debate on the existence of God between Mike Jones and Dr. Richard Carrier. Mike presents arguments for theism through idealism, the emergent universe argument, and the moral argument, asserting that a theistic explanation is more plausible and parsimonious in explaining various aspects of reality such as consciousness, morality, and the universe's emergence.  Dr. Richard Carrier defends naturalism, arguing that the explanation through a 'bubble' or nothingness leading to an infinite multiverse is simpler, more likely, and fits better with our observed reality. The debate delves into complex philosophical and scientific concepts, addressing the nature of consciousness, the possibility of a multiverse, the hard problem of consciousness, and the plausibility of moral realism. 

The session concludes with audience questions and closing arguments, offering a comprehensive discussion on the existence of God.

description:

Resolving an Alleged Biblical Error

In this video, we tackle the alleged error in Paul's mention of the ruler of Damascus in 2 Corinthians. Critics argue that Paul mistakenly referred to a governor under King Aretas, conflicting with historical sources. However, we present three scholarly explanations that showcase the complex political landscape at the time, suggesting Aretas might have briefly controlled Damascus. Through historical analysis and context, we demonstrate why Paul's account remains reliable and should not be dismissed as inaccurate.

title: Introducing: The Bayesian Islamic Dilemma
description:
üôè DONATE: https://inspiringphilosophy.com/give

Debunking Islam with Bayesian Probability: The Bayesian Islamic Dilemma

David Wood's version: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yZgMUyfQSIQ

In this video, we tackle the long-standing Islamic dilemma using Bayesian probability theory. We'll demonstrate how Islam's validity collapses under the weight of its own claims and the content of the Bible. By setting the stage with two models of reality‚ÄîChristianity and Islam‚Äîwe'll assess the evidence using Bayes' theorem. 

We differentiate between prior odds (initial beliefs) and the likelihood ratio (how well the evidence fits each model). Finally, we calculate the posterior odds to determine which model holds up better against the evidence. Through two runs of the argument, one favoring Christianity and the other Islam, we show that even with a 99% prior probability for Islam, the evidence is overwhelmingly in favor of Christianity. The video walks through the concept of prior and posterior probabilities, highlights the issues with the Islamic responses to the dilemma, and ultimately demonstrates that the evidence significantly favors Christianity.

title: How Christianity Saved Children
description:
üôè DONATE: https://inspiringphilosophy.com/give/

People don't realize how horribly children were treated in the past.  Children in Pagan societies suffered.  Ancient Roman and Greek laws and customs devalued their lives. This video explores how Christianity revolutionized the treatment of children in the ancient world, where practices like infanticide, child slavery, and sexual abuse were rampant. The introduction and spread of Christian values brought a significant shift, emphasizing the intrinsic worth of every child and fostering protective measures. Early Christian leaders condemned harmful practices, promoted orphanages, and challenged societal norms, gradually improving children's lives. This video also touches on the continued impact of Christian missionaries in various cultures worldwide, who worked to eradicate harmful practices and improve child welfare, illustrating Christianity's long-term positive influence on children globally.

title: Did Jesus Carry His Own Cross? Or Did He Need Help? | Supposed Bible Contradiction
description:
üôè DONATE: https://inspiringphilosophy.com/give/

In this episode of "Supposed Bible Contradiction", we address the commonly cited Bible contradiction concerning whether Jesus carried His own cross or if Simon of Cyrene helped him. The synoptic gospels mention Simon carrying the cross, while John states Jesus bore it Himself.  Which account is right? By highlighting literary devices and the sequence of events leading up to the crucifixion, this video offers a harmonized understanding of the gospel narratives. Watch to see how this supposed contradiction can be resolved.

00:00 Introduction: The Supposed Bible Contradiction
00:35 The Divergence in Gospel Accounts
01:08 Scholarly Perspectives on the Contradiction

title: How to Prove the Quran is from God
description:
üôè DONATE: https://inspiringphilosophy.com/give/

In this video, we critically examine claims that the Quran contains "scientific miracles". We challenge Muslims to use the Quran to make new scientific discoveries as a means of proving any scientific miracles within the text.

00:00 Introduction: Proof and Patterns
00:29 Astronomy in Ancient Cultures
02:57 Debunking the Scientific Miracles
04:21 Challenge to Muslims: Prove the Miracles

Hear Ali Dawah say it in his own words: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kUZeMcdlQYk
Ali tries to argue there still might be some scientific miracles in the Quran, like where it says there are layers of darkness in the ocean. But anyone who looked under water would see it gets darker to them the further you swim down. Aristotle, for example, in Meteorologica and in "On Colors", talked about how a medium like water can diminish and change light. It is not a scientific miracle.

title: The Shocking Truth About Biblical Names!
description:
üôè DONATE: https://inspiringphilosophy.com/give


A new peer-reviewed study has changed everything! A mathematical analysis suggests the Gospels & Acts are reliable accounts that came from historical reportage. This strengthens the overall reliability of the Gospels & Acts in new ways. A special thanks to Jason Wilson and Luuk ven de Weghe for helping with the script.

Read the pre-print of Van de Weghe and Wilson‚Äôs peer-reviewed article for free here: http://arxiv.org/abs/2403.14883

This research has passed through rigorous double-blind peer review by experts in the fields of biblical studies and statistics. It will be published this month in The Journal for the Study of the Historical Jesus, an academic publication by Brill that features critical scholarship on Jesus and his historical context. The free preprint version is identical to the closed-access publication, aside from formatting and copy editing improvements.

title: A Philosopher Reviews "The Rings of Power"
description:
I have a masters in philosophy and I am huge Tolkien nerd. I have read all his books, as well as books like, "The Lord of the Rings and Philosophy," which go deep into the philosophy of Tolkien. In this stream I'll review the Amazon show, "Rings of Power" and show where it diverges from Tolkien's philosophical beliefs. Amazon's "Rings of Power" actually injects foreign philosophical ideas into Middle Earth that makes it feel unlike the world that Tolkien created.

Have you ever wondered why Tolkien does not have Frodo defeat Sauron by casting the ring into the fire? Middle Earth has no heroes who rise up to defeat the dark lord. Why did the Valar only send 5 wizards to Middle Earth and not a whole host of Maiar to deal with Sauron? Why didn't the ents help with the war against Sauron? The reason has to do with the philosophy that was guiding Tolkien's narrative. It is not a world, like Game of Thrones, where heroes rise up to vanquish evil. Tolkien's philosophy is far different than what we see in typical fantasy novels. I'll explain what philosophy was guiding Tolkien and why he wrote as he did. I'll also explain why "Rings of Power" fails to capture Tolkien's philosophy.

title: Challenging The Documentary Hypothesis
description:
The documentary hypothesis is the view the five books of Moses (Pentateuch), were originally four separate sources of Israel's history. Alleged a redactor combined them into the present form of the Pentateuch, preserving most of the four sources. Proponents claim it is the best way to understand the history of the Pentateuch, but a lot of data challenges this assumption. I would like to thank the scholar Benjamin Kilch√∂r for helping with the script for this video.

title: The Origins of Young Earth Creationism
description:

title: Thanksgiving is Not Racist
description:
The real history of Thanksgiving is complex. Neither the pilgrims nor the American Indians were entirely good or evil. Thanksgiving today has become politicized, and the holiday is often claimed to have racist origins, but in reality, it represents a real feast from 1621, where imperfect people set aside their differences and shared a meal together. The history is less racist than you think.

title: The Case for Ancient Monotheism Documentary
description:
Monotheism is assumed to have first emerged around 500 BC, but there is an overwhelming amount of stunning evidence monotheism emerged thousands of years ago and may precede all other forms of religion.

A special thanks to James Middleton - "www.shortfusecreative.co.uk" for building to the open.

Don't forget to help us create more videos! We need your support:
https://inspiringphilosophy.org
https://www.patreon.com/inspiringphilosophy
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC5qDet6sa6rODi7t6wfpg8g/join

So a couple of things to note:

The first is I would encourage everyone to watch to the end as I will push back on some of Lang and Schmidt's conclusion and actually disagree with them on some things. This is not a video arguing for original monotheism. This is a video on ancient monotheism. That will be made clear at the end.

The second issue is there is a debate among scholars if the epic, "Enmerkar and the Lord of Aratta" should be translated to reflect a time in the past. It might be referring to a future event, but for the purposes of this video, it is mainly being used as a hook, not part of my main thrust of evidence.

Third, Schmidt argued the pigmy tribes in central Africa were one of the most, if not the most, primitive culture out there. Many of these tribes have turned out to be polytheistic, but some, like the Batwa, do seem to be monotheistic. 

Fourth, the terms, monotheism, and polytheism, are probably not the best terms to describe any religion, but they are overwhelmingly accepted by the culture we live so I am working within those parameters. This is why in the video I try to use the term "monotheistic" more than saying they were strict monotheists. I hope this becomes clear when you use catholicism as an example.

title: Biblical Archaeology: Eden
description:
üôè DONATE: https://inspiringphilosophy.com/give

I reuploaded this video because I got the Tigris and Euphrates rivers in the opposite places. Sorry for the inconvenience. 

Note* It is true the Hebrew word for headwaters mostly refers to the head of something, but the root word has so many meanings from head, chief, ends, divisions, companies, top, ridge, best, etc.
https://biblehub.com/hebrew/7218.htm

Needless to say, but the Hebrew is not necessarily referring to a place where one river splits to form 4 but can be referring to the reverse. The same can be seen with the word yatsa. It can mean to go out or came out: https://biblehub.com/hebrew/3318.htm

title: Evolutionary Argument Against Naturalism (An Introduction)
description:
Join us at: http://www.inspiringphilosophy.org

To help support this ministry click here: http://www.patreon.com/inspiringphilosophy


This is a video introducing the argument behind the evolutionary argument against naturalism developed by Alvin Plantinga. It is a remake of an older video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N4QFsKevTXs

Sources and Notes:
 
- The Virtues by Peter Geach

- http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/skepticism/

- http://www.uffl.org/vol12/moreland12.pdf

- http://www.iep.utm.edu/naturali/

- Breaking the Spell by Daniel Dennett

- http://www.calvin.edu/academic/philosophy/virtual_library/articles/plantinga_alvin/naturalism_defeated.pdf

- Untruth and Consequence by Richard Rorty

- Charles Darwin Letter to William Graham
http://www.darwinproject.ac.uk/letter/entry-13230

- Straw Gods by John Gray

- Moral Landscape by Sam Harris
(Full quote: "For instance, it is just as true to say that our logical, mathematical, and physical intuitions have not been designed by natural selection to track truth. Does this mean that we must cease to be realists with respect to physical reality? We need not look far in science to find ideas and opinions that defy easy synthesis. There are many scientific frameworks (and levels of description) that resist integration and which divide our discourse into areas of specialization, even pitting Nobel laureates in the same discipline against one another. Does this mean that we can never hope to understand what is really going on in the world? No. It mans the conversation must continue.") 
I don't see how saying "the conversation must continue" avoids the implications of this argument presented in the video. The conversation we would have is not going to track truth to begin with so it doesn't escape the self-defeating circle. To be fair, this wasn't the topic of his book, but his admission in the 'Moral Landscape' is interesting and useful for the EAAN, none the least. 

- Journal of Philosophy (LXXXIV, Oct. 87) Patricia Churchland

- Philosophy by Anthony O'Hear

title: The Book of Job Explained
description:
üôè DONATE: https://inspiringphilosophy.com/give

The Book of Job is one of the most misunderstood books in the Bible. I attempt to clear that up by offering a different perspective than most people know today. The traditional surface understanding doesn't make sense with scripture or the actual text. This new approach will clear up several misconceptions.

In regards to Job 2:3. It is interesting you brought this up, because this was something I had planned to talk about but left it because I thought I was getting to technical. Commentators like John MacArthur note the Hebrew is the same expression for what Satan uses in Job 1:9, "for nothing." Basically God has turned Satan's own words against him. God is pointing out Satan was wrong that Job only worshipped his stuff. Which is something I pointed out at the end that Satan, Job, and Job's friends were all wrong in this. God is pointing out here Job is not suffering because Satan was right about him in this, but there is deeper thing taking place. Job didn't have his stuff taken away for the cause Satan had thought.Ôªø

title: Is Christianity Slavery?
description:

One thing I've heard from New Atheists is they are trying to help us Christians and free us from the slavery of religion. I fail to see how they are offering any kind of freedom I would want. In fact, freedom is a little more complex than just being free from restrictions. Using the work of the Philosopher Isaiah Berlin, this video explains why.

*Disclaimer - Berlin was mainly writing about political philosophy and positive and negative freedom in political thought. However, from reading his work we can easily see how his definitions of different types of freedom can transcend political philosophy and apply to other areas of life and thought.
